YouTube Comment Mining & Text Analysis

Gerhard Williams

Gathering Text Data Using the YouTube API & Data Analysis Project

This is an R Markdown document that will be used to document the process of this project.

In this project we will go through the steps of gathering the YouTube data, cleaning and transforming the data, exploratory data analysis and finally a clustering analysis.

Load the YT video comments (textDisplay) in as a Corpus

A text corpus is a large and unstructured set of texts (nowadays usually electronically stored and processed) used to do statistical analysis and hypothesis testing, checking occurrences or validating linguistic rules within a specific language territory. - https://guides.library.uq.edu.au/research-techniques/text-mining-analysis/language-corpora

##### Load the YT video comments (textDisplay) in as a Corpus ####

docs <- Corpus(VectorSource(comments1$textDisplay))

Clean up the doc texts/Text Transformation - stopwords, numbers, etc.

#### Clean up the doc texts/Text Transformation - stopwords, numbers, etc. ####
# Remove numbers
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeNumbers)

# Convert the text to lower case
##docs <- tm_map(docs, content_transformer(tolower)) - due to non-english alphabet text this causes problems

docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, stopwords("english"))

docs <- tm_map(docs, removePunctuation)

# specify your stopwords as a character vector
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, c("amp", "the"))

# Eliminate extra white spaces
docs <- tm_map(docs, stripWhitespace)

Create Term Document Matrix

######## Term Document Matrix #####

dtm <- TermDocumentMatrix(docs)
m <- as.matrix(dtm)
v <- sort(rowSums(m),decreasing=TRUE)
d <- data.frame(word = names(v),freq=v)

Find Associations/Correlations with the Words (Armin, Love, & Trance)

  • Load in package and create list of source words to be correlated with
#### Find Associations ####
library(tm) #load package for findAssocs function

#### list of correlation source words ####
corterms <- c("armin","love","trance")

print(corterms)
## [1] "armin"  "love"   "trance"
  • Create function that creates a dataframe with words associated with Armin, Love & Trance at a level higher than 0.30
#### create function to dataframe with correlations for each selected word ####
corrfun <- function(x) {
  corrdf1 <- NULL
  for(i in x) {
    corrdf <- rbind((as.data.frame(findAssocs(dtm, terms = i, corlimit = 0.3))))
    corrdf$SourceWord <- i
    colnames(corrdf)[1] <- "Correlation.Percent"
    colnames(corrdf)[2] <- "Correlation.Source.Word"
    ## make rownames into a column with the secondary correlated word
    corrdf <- cbind(rownames(corrdf), data.frame(corrdf, row.names=NULL))
    ## take the id column and make it the 'Correlated.Word'
    colnames(corrdf)[1] <- "word"
    corrdf1 <- rbind(corrdf1, corrdf)
    #print(corrdf1)
  }
  return(corrdf1)
}
  • Apply the function to the list of source words
## apply the function to the list of corterms
corrfundf <- corrfun(corterms)

head(corrfundf)

Cleaning the new correlation dataframe

#### cleaning the corrfundf dataframe ####

#convert Correlation.Word from Factors to Characters
corrfundf$word <- as.character(corrfundf$word)

#remove more href links
corrfundf <- subset(corrfundf, grepl("href.", corrfundf$word) !=TRUE)
corrfundf <- subset(corrfundf, grepl("-", corrfundf$word) !=TRUE)
corrfundf <- subset(corrfundf, grepl("href.", corrfundf$word) !=TRUE)

## remove non-alpha numeric symbols and convert non-english alphabet letters to english letters
library(stringr)
corrfundf$word <- str_replace_all(corrfundf$word, "[^[:alnum:]]", "")
corrfundf$word <- str_replace_all(corrfundf$word, "[^a-zA-Z0-9]", "")

corrfundf$word <- iconv(corrfundf$word, from = 'UTF-8', to = 'ASCII//TRANSLIT')

# remove the empty rows
corrfundf <- corrfundf %>% filter(word != "")

head(corrfundf)
##     word Correlation.Percent Correlation.Source.Word

##### Merge 'd' dataframe and corrfunddf by word to attach freq variable ####

corrfundf <- merge(d, corrfundf, by.x = "word", by.y = "word")

corrfundf$Correlation.Source.Word <- as.factor(corrfundf$Correlation.Source.Word)

Scatter Plot of Word Frequency and Source Word Correlation Percent (Source Words: Armin, Trance, Love)

#### create ggplot scatterplot freq~correlation percent with Source.Word as factor ####

#tooltip
corrfundf$tooltipscatwords <- paste0("Word: ",corrfundf$word, "<br/>", "Frequency: ", corrfundf$freq,
"<br/>", "Correlation with ", "<b>", corrfundf$Correlation.Source.Word, "</b>", ": ", corrfundf$Correlation.Percent)

scatplot <- ggplot(corrfundf, aes(x=Correlation.Percent, y=freq, color=Correlation.Source.Word, tooltip=tooltipscatwords, data_id = tooltipscatwords)) +
  geom_point_interactive() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  ggtitle("Word Frequency & Correlation with Source Words \n Armin van Buuren's 2019 Ultra Music Festival Set", subtitle = "Words with at least a 30% Correlation to the Source Word") +
  xlab("Correlation with Source Word") +
  ylab("Frequency (log 10)")

ggiraph(code = print(scatplot), width_svg = 8, height_svg = 4, tooltip_extra_css = tooltip_css, hover_css = "cursor:pointer;fill:red;r:3pt;")

  geom_point_interactive() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  ggtitle(" Scaled Word Frequency & Correlation with Armin Scatter Plot \n Armin van Buuren's 2019 Ultra Music Festival Set", subtitle = "Words with at least a 30% Correlation to the Source Word") +

Finding the Optimal Amount of Clusters

  • Will use the K-Means/Naive K-Means clustering algorithm
  • Will use Euclidean Distance (default in fviz_nbclust function) because the matrix/dataframe is only two columns with every row filled - Manhattan Distance would be considered if the data had more dimensions.

KMEANS & Elbow Method

#### Elbow method ####
set.seed(1776)
fviz_nbclust(ytcorrfreqarmindf, kmeans, method = "wss") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 3, linetype = 2)+
  labs(subtitle = "Elbow Method")

  • Here we see that the elbow method suggests that the data should be divided into 4 clusters, maybe even 5. The elbow plot shows how much variance/sum of squares (y-axis) is explained by the number of clusters on the (x-axis). The more clusters we have, the lower the total within sum of squares will be. However, we want to find the optimal amount of clusters which comes at a point where the curve of the elbow plot is flat. Each additional cluster results in marginally less and less within group variance.

Silhouette Method

#### Silhouette method ####
set.seed(1776)
fviz_nbclust(ytcorrfreqarmindf, kmeans, method = "silhouette")+
  labs(subtitle = "Silhouette Method")

#silhouette method suggests using 5 clusters - use highest average silhouette width

  • The Silhouette plot shows the silhouette coefficient (estimate of average distance between clusters) for different values of k (# of clusters). A higher silhouette coefficient or average silhouette width, typically means that is the optimal number of clusters.

  • From the above plot we see that 4 clusters is the optimum as ithas the highest silhouette width

Gap Stat Method

#### Gap Stat Method ####
set.seed(1776)
fviz_nbclust(ytcorrfreqarmindf, kmeans, nstart = 25,  method = "gap_stat", nboot = 100)+
  labs(subtitle = "Gap Statistic Method")

  • The gap statistic compares the total intracluster variation for different values of k with their expected values under null reference distribution of the data (i.e.a distribution with no obvious clustering). - UC Davis Business Analytics - https://uc-r.github.io/kmeans_clustering

  • The first local maximum will be chosen as the optimal number of clusters.

#### Gap Stat Method 2nd####
library(cluster)
set.seed(1776)
gap_stat <- clusGap(ytcorrfreqarmindf, FUN = kmeans, nstart=25, K.max = 20, B = 10)

fviz_gap_stat(gap_stat)

gapDF <- as.data.frame(gap_stat$Tab)

gapplot <- ggplot(gapDF, aes(x=1:nrow(gapDF))) +
  geom_line(aes(y=logW, color="logw - Observed")) +
  geom_point_interactive(aes(y=logW, color="logw - Observed",tooltip=paste0("Gap: ", gap), data.id=rownames(gapDF))) +
  geom_line(aes(y=E.logW, color="E.logw - Expected")) +
  geom_point_interactive(aes(y=E.logW, color="E.logw - Expected",tooltip=paste0("Gap: ",gap), data.id=rownames(gapDF))) +
  labs(x="Number of Clusters") +
  scale_color_manual("",
                     breaks = c("logw - Observed", "E.logw - Expected"),
                     values = c("logw - Observed" = "blue", "E.logw - Expected" = "green"))

ggiraph(code = print(gapplot), width_svg = 8, height_svg = 4, tooltip_extra_css = tooltip_css, hover_css = "cursor:pointer;fill:red;r:3pt;")

* When the number of clusters is increased, the gap statistic has higher local maximums. This suggests that there are many small subclusters within the 2 larger separated clusters.

Merge Clustering Results to Original Dataframe - Preparation for CSV Download

#### assigning the clusters to the data for export to csv ####

#put cluster info into dataframe
armin.w.clust <- as.data.frame(res.km$cluster)

#turn the index column into a column of the df
armin.w.clust <- cbind(rownames(armin.w.clust), data.frame(armin.w.clust, row.names=NULL))

## take the id column and make it the 'Correlated.Word'
colnames(armin.w.clust)[1] <- "word"

## merge the original dataframe w/ freq & correlation % with the cluster df
armin.w.clust.df <- merge(ytcorrfreqarmin, armin.w.clust, by.x = "word", by.y = "word")
## rename the 4th column to cluster
colnames(armin.w.clust.df)[4] <- "cluster"

## arrange dataframe by cluster
armin.w.clust.df <- armin.w.clust.df %>%
  arrange(cluster)
